{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16605"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16605"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.1,0.05,0.78]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9296"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61498"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5303"},{"type":"tags","id":"10604"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22046"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pills are commonly prescribed for contraception. They contain both oestrogen and progestogen components.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of combined oral contraceptive pills?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct inhibition of implantation","Disruption of corpus luteum formation","Prevention of fertilisation through cervical mucus changes","Direct suppression of follicular development","Suppression of ovulation through hypothalamic-pituitary feedback"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of combined oral contraceptive pills is \u003Cstrong\u003Esuppression of ovulation through hypothalamic-pituitary feedback\u003C/strong\u003E. The oestrogen and progestogen components suppress follicle stimulating hormone and luteinising hormone release, preventing follicular development and ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect inhibition of implantation\u003C/strong\u003E: While combined oral contraceptives do cause endometrial changes that make implantation less favourable, this is a secondary mechanism. The primary effect occurs earlier in the reproductive cycle by preventing ovulation altogether.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of corpus luteum formation\u003C/strong\u003E: The corpus luteum cannot form because ovulation is prevented by hormonal suppression. This is a consequence of the primary mechanism rather than a direct effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevention of fertilisation through cervical mucus changes\u003C/strong\u003E: While cervical mucus changes do occur that make sperm transport more difficult, this is a secondary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect suppression of follicular development\u003C/strong\u003E: Combined oral contraceptives prevent follicular development through hormonal feedback mechanisms rather than any direct suppressive effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe negative feedback on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis prevents the mid-cycle surge of luteinising hormone that triggers ovulation. Without ovulation, pregnancy cannot occur regardless of any secondary mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Combined oral contraceptive pills contain both oestrogen and progestogen components that work together to prevent pregnancy.","The primary mechanism of action is suppression of ovulation through negative feedback on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis.","Secondary mechanisms include cervical mucus thickening and endometrial changes that inhibit implantation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61498"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16605"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61498"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T20:53:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T20:57:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9296"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75997"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junio